<TITLE> Govt to return Tk 61 lakh borrowed from vested property fund </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 17 (bdnews24.com)  The government has begun process to pay back Tk 61 lakh which it had taken from Vested Property Fund of the land ministry six years ago, a senior ministry official said. The money, according to the ministry, was taken from the fund to meet some urgent needs between 1999 and 2004 and was supposed to be refunded later. The money was used to conduct court cases of the land ministry, pay for its officers' training, car registration, to purchase computers and spend on the ministry's recruitment process. Joint secretary (law) Nikhil Ranjan Mandal told bdnews24.com that it is the land ministry that has taken the initiative to refund the money. He said they have also written to the finance ministry for not objecting the issue and as soon as their no-objection note is received, the money would be paid back. A land ministry official, preferring not to be named, said the issue recently came up for discussion when the minister and secretary of the land ministry gave directives to take necessary steps to return the money. Nikhil Ranjan Mandal said no irregularities were made in using the money from the Vested Property Fund. There is around Tk 80 crore deposited in the fund which came from lease of vested properties and sales of assets, he added. 
